Slide 1: Acknowledging Reality - The "As-Is" State
Title: Pragmatic Modernization: Bridging to the Target State
Subtitle: Acknowledging our current constraints and planning a safe transition
Current Constraints (The Reality Check):
No Formal Domains: Packaged Business Capabilities (PBCs) and formal Domain-Driven boundaries are not yet established.
Centralized Bottlenecks: API Gateways are currently operated as a centralized IT function, not federated to development teams.
Heavy ESB Footprint: The enterprise relies on a monolithic ESB for heavy orchestration, data transformation, and legacy system connectivity.
The Strategy:
We will not attempt a "rip and replace" of the ESB.
We will implement an "API Façade" pattern to decouple consumers from the legacy backend.
We will use the Strangler Fig pattern at the Routing Layer to safely and incrementally migrate capabilities out of the ESB over time.
Slide 2: Tactical Routing Pattern (The "Right Now")
Title: Tactical Routing: The API Façade over Legacy ESB
Scenario: How do we route hybrid cloud traffic today, knowing the ESB must do the heavy lifting?
The Tactical Path:
Cloud App → DC Ingress API Gateway (Centralized) → Central ESB → Legacy Core
Why this is our Tactical Standard:
Pros: Leverages existing ESB investments for protocol translation (e.g., REST to SOAP/MQ) and complex legacy orchestration. Requires zero immediate refactoring of backend code.
Cons: The Central API Gateway and ESB remain dual bottlenecks. High risk of duplicating logic across both platforms.
Critical Mitigation (The "Line in the Sand"):
To prevent compounding our technical debt, we enforce a strict boundary:
The API Gateway ONLY handles Security (OAuth, Rate Limiting, Threat Protection).
The ESB ONLY handles Legacy Translation (Protocol mapping, orchestration).
Rule: Absolutely no new business logic is allowed in either layer.
Slide 3: The Strangler Fig Migration Path
Title: The Strangler Fig Execution
Subtitle: How we evolve from a Centralized ESB to Decentralized Domains
Phase 1: Façade & Freeze (Months 1-6)
Expose all legacy ESB endpoints as clean, RESTful APIs through the Central Ingress API Gateway.
Action: Freeze the ESB. No net-new business capabilities are allowed to be built inside the ESB.
Phase 2: Intercept & Branch (Months 6-12)
Identify a "low-risk, high-value" capability (e.g., Customer Address Lookup) and rebuild it as a standalone microservice.
Action: Update the Central API Gateway routing table. Path /api/v1/customer/address is routed to the new microservice. All other /api/v1/customer/* traffic continues to fall back to the ESB.
Phase 3: Domain Decentralization (Months 12-24)
As multiple microservices form a "Domain" (e.g., Customer Management), introduce the first lightweight Domain API Gateway to manage them.
Action: The Central Ingress Gateway now routes traffic to the Domain Gateway instead of the ESB. The ESB is systematically starved of traffic.
Slide 4: Mitigating the Centralized Gateway Risk
Title: Operating a Centralized Gateway Safely
Subtitle: Preventing the Gateway from becoming the "New ESB"
While we rely on a centralized API Gateway team today, we must implement these guardrails to avoid slowing down time-to-market:
Configuration as Code (GitOps):
Network and routing rules must be managed in Git. Developers submit pull requests (PRs) with their routing needs (Swagger/OpenAPI specs), which the Gateway team approves, triggering automated deployment.
"Dumb Pipes" Policy Enforcement:
The Architecture Review Board (ARB) will reject any API design that attempts to use the Gateway for payload transformation (e.g., changing JSON structures) or multi-endpoint chaining.
Federated Analytics:
Even if the Gateway is centrally managed, logging and monitoring dashboards (e.g., Datadog, Splunk) must be filtered and federated back to the application developers so they can debug their own traffic.
